{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Domžale Sports Park | nickname = | image = Domzale Stadium 2014.jpg | image_size = 270px | fullname = Športni park Domžale | location = [[Domžale]], [[Slovenia]] | coordinates = {{coord|46|8|13|N|14|36|8|E|display=it|type:landmark}} | broke_ground = | built = 1948 | opened = | renovated = 1976, 1997, 1999, 2004, 2006 | expanded = 2003–2004 | record_attendance = 3,100 | closed = | demolished = | owner = Municipality of [[Domžale]] | operator = | surface = Grass | construction_cost = | architect = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = [[NK Domžale]] (1948–present) | seating_capacity = 3,100 | dimensions = 105 × 68 metres | scoreboard = }} '''Domžale Sports Park''' ({{lang-sl|Športni park Domžale}}) or '''Domžale Stadium''' ({{lang-sl|Stadion Domžale}}) is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Domžale]], [[Slovenia]]. It is currently used mostly for [[football (soccer)|football]] matches and is the home ground of [[NK Domžale]]. The stadium, which was built in 1948, currently holds 3,100 spectators. The stadium was renovated and modernized in 1997 and 1999. Work on the new western stand started in October 2003 and was finished in April 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://siol.net/sportal/nogomet/sportni-park-domzale-75299|title=Športni park Domžale|author=Sportal|publisher=[[Siol]]|language=sl|accessdate=24 May 2018|date=10 December 2007}}</ref> In June 2006 the stadium received floodlights, mounted on four concrete towers and placed at each corner of the stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.delo.si/sport/domzalski-stadion-z-novo-razsvetljavo.html|language=sl|publisher=[[Delo (Slovenia)|Delo]]|date=31 May 2006|accessdate=21 July 2017|title=Domžalski stadion z novo razsvetljavo}}</ref>
