{{use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = The Village | nickname = Malahide Cricket Club Ground | image = Malahide Cricket Ground 2013.jpg | caption = 2013 ODI between Ireland and England | country = Ireland | location = [[Malahide]], [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland]] | establishment = 1861 | seating_capacity = 11,500<ref name="claim11500">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/566963.html|title=Malahide to host England ODI|access-date=6 February 2018|date=1 June 2012|dead-url=no|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917170302/www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/566963.html|archive-date=17 September 2016|website=[[ESPN]]cricinfo}}</ref> | coordinates = {{coord|53.4493|N|6.1612|W|type:landmark_region:IE|display=title,inline}} | owner = [[Malahide Cricket Club]]<ref name="TheOwner">[http://www.malahidecc.com/ Malahide Cricket Club]</ref>{{Additional citation needed|reason=unclear ownership with alternative suggestions and existing citation to club homepage only inadequate|date=February 2018}} | operator = [[Cricket Ireland]] | tenants = [[Ireland Cricket Team]] | end1 = Dublin Road End | end2 = Castle End | international = true | onlytestdate = 11–15 May | onlytestyear = 2018 | onlytesthome = Ireland | onlytestaway = Pakistan <!--| firsttestdate = 11–15 May | firsttestyear = 2018 | firsttesthome = Ireland | firsttestaway = Pakistan--> | lasttestdate = | lasttestyear = | lasttesthome = | lasttestaway = | firstodidate = 3 September | firstodiyear = 2013 | firstodihome = Ireland | firstodiaway = England | lastodidate = 21 May | lastodiyear = 2017 | lastodihome = Ireland | lastodiaway = New Zealand | firstt20idate = 17 July | firstt20iyear = 2015 | firstt20ihome = Nepal | firstt20iaway = Papua New Guinea | lastt20idate = 29 June | lastt20iyear = 2018 | lastt20ihome = Ireland | lastt20iaway = India | date = 29 June | year = 2018 |publictransit = [[Malahide railway station]] | source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/ground/58607.html ESPN Cricinfo }}
'''Malahide Cricket Club Ground''' or '''The Village''' is a cricket ground in [[Malahide]], [[Ireland]] situated in the Lady Acre field of [[Malahide Castle]] grounds. The ground is owned by the [[Malahide Cricket Club]].<ref name="TheOwner"/> The ground has been developed to a capacity of 11,500 making it [[Ireland]]'s biggest cricket venue and officially opened for international cricket in 2013. In November 2017, it was confirmed as the venue for Ireland's first [[Test cricket|Test match]], when they played [[Pakistani cricket team in Ireland in 2018|Pakistan in May 2018]].<ref name="IrePak">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/42066074 |title=Malahide to host Ireland's first Test match when they play Pakistan in May |accessdate=21 November 2017 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>
==International cricket== In September 2013, [[International Cricket Council]] cleared the ground to host international cricket. The ground hosted its first international cricket match when home team [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] played against [[England cricket team|England]] with England winning by six wickets after captain [[Eoin Morgan]] hit 124 not out on what had been his home ground in his youth.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23926135 bbc]</ref> The capacity was designed to be increased to 11500 using temporary grandstands and hospitality tents making it the biggest in Ireland with a record attendance for the Island of Ireland of over 10,000.<ref name="claim11500"/><ref name="Over10000">{{cite news|url=http://www.newstalk.com/Cricket-Ireland-to-get-largest-ever-attendance-tomorrow-|title= Cricket Ireland to get largest ever attendance tomorrow|last=Flynn|first=Odran|date=2 September 2013|access-date=5 February 2018|website=[[Newstalk]]|dead-url=no|archive-date=5 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205195226/http://www.newstalk.com/Cricket-Ireland-to-get-largest-ever-attendance-tomorrow-}}</ref>
The ground became Ireland's third venue for international cricket, the other two being [[Castle Avenue]] in [[Dublin]] and the Civil Service Cricket Club Ground at [[Stormont (cricket ground)|Stormont]].
Malahide was also confirmed as the stage for two [[Twenty20]] games against the touring [[South Africa A cricket team|South Africa A]] side in 2013.
It was selected as a venue to host matches in the [[2015 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier]] tournament.<ref name="2015Fixtures">{{cite web |url=http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2015/media-releases/87946/icc-announces-schedule-of-icc-world-twenty20-qualifier-2015 |title=ICC announces schedule of ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier 2015 |accessdate=14 May 2015 |work=International Cricket Council}}</ref>
==International centuries== On the very first Test cricket match for Ireland, [[Kevin O'Brien (cricketer)|Kevin O'Brien]] scored the maiden Test century at the venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/stats/index.html?class=1;filter=advanced;ground=974;orderby=start;runsmin1=100;runsval1=runs;size=200;template=results;type=batting;view=innings|title=Statistics / Statsguru / Test cricket / Batting records|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>
